│ The user wants me to fix a crash in the LLVM SLP vectorizer. The crash is an assertion failure, `trying to erase instruction │
│ with users`, which occurs during horizontal reduction vectorization.                                                         │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The analysis of the reproducer reveals that the vectorizer identifies a chain of `xor` instructions as a horizontal          │
│ reduction. One of the operands in this reduction chain, `%or92`, is also used by a PHI node, `%p1`, which is outside the     │
│ reduction chain. When the vectorizer attempts to transform the reduction chain, it tries to delete the original scalar       │
│ instruction `%or92`. However, since `%p1` still uses `%or92`, the assertion fails.                                           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The correct fix is to add a safety check. Before attempting to vectorize a horizontal reduction, the vectorizer must verify  │
│ that no instruction within the reduction candidate tree has users outside of that tree. If an external user is found, the    │
│ vectorizer should abort the transformation for that candidate.                                                               │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ This check should be placed in the `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` function in `SLPVectorizer.cpp`, just before the call  │
│ to `vectorizeTree`. The logic involves iterating through the instructions in the `ReductionOps` map, collecting them into a  │
│ set, and then for each instruction, checking if any of its operands have users that are not in this set.                     │
